body:
@peterjc123 @jywu-msft 


MKL-DNN supports the Winograd algorithm for convolutions with the following sizes:

- 2D convolution (i.e. spatial depth d=1)
- kernel sizes kh=3,kw=3.
- strides sh=sw=1.
- Inference - Based on convolution sizes, MKLDNN chooses between two different tile sizes F(2x2, 3x3) or F(4x4, 3x3).

We need to add checks to make sure that inputs of correct sizes are provided to mkldnn convolution.

More details are at https://intel.github.io/mkl-dnn/winograd_convolution.html
@sreekanth-yalachigere Yes, I tested all the convs generated by `mkldnn-verbose=1` with benchdnn and found out that there is one layer that doesn't fit in the size requirements.

After adding some if conditions before applying the Winograd algorithm, I managed to run the whole graph. But now the problem is that the runtime performance is not so good. My model has dynamic input dimensions so the computation graph will be constructed every time I feed in new input. At the same time, the weights are transformed into the Winograd format multiple times, too. How can I reuse the weights and avoid these reshaping?

We are already saving reordered [weights](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/938200de9b800e436349ff64a57898d4139f932e/onnxruntime/core/providers/mkldnn/subgraph/mkldnn_conv.h#L382). 

dynamic input shapes are not supported yet. Do you have a graph without dynamic input dimensions? Can you check the performance of Winograd?

Actually, when I tried something like VGG16 that is transformed from PyTorch, it crashed with the message `Segementation fault (core dumped)`. My changes in the code are available here: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/compare/master...peterjc123:winograd The model is stored in [Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/open?id=18DUCTm7avQn43UVHrDwO1TVc1GEq2IR8). Could you please take a look?

> We are already saving reordered [weights](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/938200de9b800e436349ff64a57898d4139f932e/onnxruntime/core/providers/mkldnn/subgraph/mkldnn_conv.h#L382).

As for the performance of the model, looks like it is taking up much time in `wino_reshape` for the first run. The running time after that is much faster. Looks like you are correct.

@peterjc123, I've added Winograd support to my task list. I will update you soon. 
Thanks
Hi all, what is the progress on this as a matter of fact quite important feature?
This issue has been automatically closed due to inactivity. Please reactivate if further support is needed.
